>Upgrade & Build Advice
Post build list or current specs including MONITOR: https://pcpartpicker.com/
Provide specific use cases (e.g. 4K editing, high FPS gaming)
State budget and country

>News
- Recent releases:
- Nvidia RTX 4080 16GB - 4080 12GB version unlaunched
- Nvidia RTX 4090 24GB
- Intel 13th generation CPUs - supports DDR4 + DDR5
- AMD Ryzen 7000 series CPUs - DDR5 only
- Intel ARC GPUs released - Bad performance on pre-DX12 games.

>CPUs
For light usage, consider an Intel i3 or Ryzen 3/G.
For gaming, consider an Intel i5 (K if you want overclocking) or a Ryzen 5.
For multithreaded performance, consider an Intel i7 or a Ryzen 9. Get a Threadripper for heavy-duty workloads.

>GPUs
For gaming, check out the benchmarks for whatever games you play and pick whatever performs best.
For productivity, you will want to buy a Nvidia Card for CUDA, nvenc, better software support in general.

>PSUs
https://cultists.network/140/psu-tier-list/

>SSDs
Use an NVMe Drive for your operating system.
Standouts: Hynix P41, Kingston KC3000, WD Black SN850X
https://ssd.borecraft.com/

https://www.build-gaming-computers.com/motherboards-with-bios-flashback.html

[{'no': 90231999, 'now': '12/11/22(Sun)06:45:18', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': 'poweramp (only proprietary app, music player)
f-droid (foss software store)
tachiyomi (manga reader)
newpipe (for youtube)
blue clover fork (4chan)
bromite (browser because vanadium has ads)', 'time': 1670759118, 'resto': 90231208}, {'no': 90232052, 'now': '12/11/22(Sun)06:50:10', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>90231744
>>90231864
>>90231965
>>90231999
Cheers anons.
How about map/navigation and run/fitness tracking? Is Organic Maps usable for GPS? Or is this one thing that I'm better off using sandboxed Google for?', 'time': 1670759410, 'resto': 90231208}, {'no': 90232183, 'now': '12/11/22(Sun)07:02:34', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>90232052
I've found the GPS works fine on Organic Maps. You have to download the maps beforehand, but once you have your city, you're pretty much good to go. I think a lot of people get a text to speech program for it, but I've heard they're pretty janky. I just keep it on a dock in my car and glance over at it to make a note of where to go next. Sometimes there will be a detour for construction on the route it picks, but once you start going down the detour, it will figure out a new route for you pretty quickly. It also doesn't have every business labelled, but you can select unlabelled buildings and it'll route you there anyway. It does not have closing times for businesses labelled, so if you're a fatass who likes late night fast food runs, you're out of luck.', 'time': 1670760154, 'resto': 90231208}, {'no': 90232252, 'now': '12/11/22(Sun)07:09:12', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>90232183
Word, thanks anon. I never use navigation narration anyway so that's a non-issue. I will miss having business hours and reviews available on the map (mainly for times when I want to try a new restaurant on the weekend) but if push comes to shove I can always just search that info on the web.', 'time': 1670760552, 'resto': 90231208}, {'no': 90232259, 'now': '12/11/22(Sun)07:09:53', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>90232052
I am >>90231744
I forgot to mention that you can use the Play Store without the need to install sandboxed play services. Just get Aurora Store from F-droid. It's a privacy Play Store frontend. Some apps (like the one from Google) wont work regardless, for that you will need to get play services and services framework.
For maps, I used OsmAnd, Organic Maps and Magic Earth. Magic Earth is the one I use now, bear in mind that it is not open source yet. The devs have said that they will eventually go open source, but they also says that they are already committed to privacy.
I also use Google Camera, it takes way better pictures compared to the Graphene camera app. For that you will need Gcam services provider (if you decide to install play services and services framework, make sure to remove gcam services provider, those will go in conflict with each other).', 'time': 1670760593, 'resto': 90231208}]

READ THE WIKI! & help by contributing:
https://wiki.installgentoo.com/wiki/Home_server

>NAS Case Guide. Feel free to add to it:
https://wiki.installgentoo.com/wiki/Home_server/Case_guide

/hsg/ is about learning and expanding your horizons. Know all about NAS? Learn virtualization. Spun up some VMs? Learn about networking by standing up a OPNsense/pfsense box and configuring some VLANs. There's always more to learn and chances to grow. Think you’re god-tier already? Setup OpenStack and report back.

>What software should I run?
Install Gentoo. Or whatever flavor of *nix is best for the job or most comfy for you. Jellyfin to replace Netflix, nextcloud to replace Googlel, ampache to replace spotify, the list goes on and on. Look at the awesome self-hosted list and ask.

>Why should I have a home server?
Learn something new. De-botnet your life. Serving applications to yourself, your family, and your frens feels good. Put your /g/ skills to good use for yourself and those close to you. Store their data with proper availability redundancy and backups and serve it back to them with a /comfy/ easy to use interface.

Users of all levels are welcome.
Share Windows tools, utilities, tips & tricks.

FAQ:
>How do I activate Windows?
https://github.com/massgravel/Microsoft-Activation-Scripts
HWID mimics upgrade activation to generate a permanent legitimate license.

>>Which version should I install?
>Home/Pro
Comes with bloatware apps (games, music, news, weather, etc)
>Education/Workstation/Enterprise
Comes with basic system apps.
>LTSC / IoT LTSC
LTSC = 5 years support, VL/KMS only
IoT LTSC = 10 years support, HWID only
Comes with Win32 system apps, no MS Store, no feature updates, security updates only.
If you need MS Store, run this in cmd: 
wsreset -i


>Do I even need IoT LTSC?
W10 Home/Pro/Edu/WS/Ent editions end support in 10/2025, LTSC in 2027, IoT LTSC lasts until 2032.

>How do I activate Office?
https://github.com/abbodi1406/KMS_VL_ALL_AIO/releases
Installs a KMS server emulator, not ideal as KMS trips AV sometimes and deactivates. Alternatively, use MSOffice through your browser since it's free. As a last resort, you can try OnlyOffice/LibreOffice/WPS/Polaris and set it to save as MSOffice file formats.

>Where can I get Windows/Office ISOs?
https://massgrave.dev/genuine-installation-media.html
Other sources:
https://pastebin.com/p6b3N9w2
https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/deployoffice/overview-office-deployment-tool

>Is Optimize-Offline worth it?
>Should I debloat?
If you need to ask, then no. You WILL break something and then come crying about updates/store/feature not working.

/TWS/ Hall of Fame:
• https://www.scarbir.com/truewireless

• Why use a PMP instead of a phone?
>Better DAC/amp
>More output power so it can drive higher impedance headphones
>Smaller sizes than phones for activities like exercise
>Physical buttons
>Headphone jacks
>Some people can't use smartphone at work/use dumbphones

• How to request advice:
>Budget
>Source (phone or PMP)
>Location
>Kind (in-ear or earbuds)
>Sound signature (or genres you like, important!)
>Past gear and your thoughts on them (important!)

Good Morning Dra/g/on Maids!

I have a Writing Computer. I use her like a typewriter. She serves no purpose beyond be comfortable for using Texlive for a few hours at a time. I got her because I like UMPCs and thumb typing with a mechanical keyboard.

I have two minor complaints about the device related to keyboard and I am hoping somebody here knows how to modify the machine to make her nicer.

>keyboard light
Writing Computer has a wonderful keyboard. It is a thumb typing mechanical keyboard. Unfortunately it is not lit, so it is restricted to times when I have light.

Is it possible to add backlighting to the keyboard? As a workaround I can buy a lamp, but I would prefer the machine have this capability in case I am outside at night.

>display toggle
The original TRS-80 Model 100 had a nice feature where you can flip a switch and it cuts power to the display. This is useful for saving battery. In my workflow, when Texlive is compiling, I would like to switch the display off to save battery and just switch it back on to see results.

Ideally a different toggle switch would control turning keyboard backlight on/off.

>Used machines are plentiful and cheap

ThinkWiki - General info about ThinkPads/specs

Classic models:
>X220/X230 - 12", 768p, cheap and light
>T420/T430 - 14", 900p (1080p w/mod board), Ivy Bridge support on T420 w/coreboot, quad core upgrade, classic keyboard mod on xx30 series
>T520/530; W520/530 - 15", 1080p, DTR, 32GB RAM on quad core models
>T440p/540p; W540/1 - last ThinkPads with socketed processors, easily replaceable trackpad (W541 doesn't need trackpad replacement)
>T440s/T450(s)/T460(s)/T470(s) - ultraportables, good battery life
>T480 - last ThinkPad with swappable battery, T25 keyboard mod, excellent performance/battery life, getting cheaper

Upgraded models:
>X2100 - X200/X201
>X62/X63 - X61
>T700 - T60

BIOS replacement:
https://coreboot.org - T440p, X131e, X1C1, and xx30 series (no 61) or older

Additional resources:

UEFI patches:
